The names oi the early prudentes who lived under the free Republic are collected by Pomponius in Dig. r. z. a. 35-39; the first is that of Papirius, whose compilation oi the leges regiae has been already noticed. These earliest lawyers are styled prudentes not because their knowledge of the law was more scientific, less empirical, than that oi other men, but rather because they knew it more luily; a philosophical treatment of law had hot yet commenced‚ and such distinction as there was between their legal knowledge and that of the ordinary citizen was quantitative rather than qualitative.
